  "insights": {
    "timeline": "The pattern of attacking pressure in WC2026 matches reveals that teams tend to build momentum in the first 20 minutes of each half, with a notable spike in shots, corners, and goals, before the hydration breaks at around 23 minutes in the first half and 68 minutes in the second half. This suggests that teams are able to establish a rhythm and create scoring opportunities early on, but the breaks seem to slightly disrupt this momentum, as the pressure tends to dip immediately after the hydration stops. However, the fact that pressure picks up again shortly after the breaks indicates that teams are able to quickly regain their rhythm and continue to create chances. The timing of the hydration breaks appears to be well-placed, allowing teams to recharge without significantly impacting the overall flow of the match.",
    "scatter": "The statistics from the FIFA World Cup 2026 show that teams who are actively pressing their opponents, meaning they launch at least two attacks within a 10-minute period before a hydration break, tend to lose their momentum after the break. This is evident in both the first and second halves of matches, where a significant majority of teams that were pressing before the break saw a drop in their performance afterwards. In practical terms, this means that when a team is aggressively pushing forward and creating scoring opportunities before a hydration break, they often struggle to maintain that same level of intensity and pressure on their opponents after the break. This loss of momentum can be a crucial factor in determining the outcome of a match, as teams that can't sustain their pressure may find themselves on the back foot and vulnerable to counter-attacks.",
    "deltas": "The statistics from the FIFA World Cup 2026 show that teams tend to have a slight increase in actions per minute after the first half hydration break, with an average increase of 0.040 actions per minute, indicating a brief surge in intensity. However, this momentum is short-lived, as the second half sees a negligible decrease in actions per minute, suggesting that the break has a disrupting effect on the teams' rhythm. The fact that teams that were pressing, marked as \u2605, tend to have a negative change in actions per minute after the break, while non-pressing teams see a positive change, implies that the hydration break can be a momentum killer, particularly for teams that were aggressively pushing the pace of the game. This distribution suggests that the break can be a turning point in the match, allowing teams to regroup and adjust their strategy, which can potentially shift the balance of the game",
    "summary": "The statistics show that teams that employ a pressing strategy tend to lose momentum during hydration breaks, while teams that don't press gain an advantage. Specifically, in the first half, pressing teams saw a significant drop in performance, losing about 0.124 units of intensity per minute, whereas non-pressing teams gained about 0.152 units per minute, effectively evening out the playing field. This \"equalizer effect\" is also observed in the second half, albeit to a lesser extent, where pressing teams still lost ground, but non-pressing teams gained less, indicating that hydration breaks can be a crucial factor in shifting the balance of a match. Overall, these numbers suggest that hydration breaks can be a turning point in a game, allowing non-pressing teams to regain their footing and potentially change the outcome of the match."
